00:13:43,305 --> 00:13:44,826
The original design for Slime Rancher

252
00:13:44,866 --> 00:13:47,527
had them just jumping higher and higher and higher

253
00:13:47,567 --> 00:13:48,508
until they would get out.

254
00:13:49,569 --> 00:13:50,790
and that kind of felt cheap.

255
00:13:51,010 --> 00:13:51,871
They still do that.

256
00:13:52,772 --> 00:13:55,435
The slimes get bouncier the hungrier they are,

257
00:13:55,896 --> 00:13:59,800
but the stacking is what really sold it.

258
00:14:00,321 --> 00:14:02,843
And it was because the player can then look at that

259
00:14:03,024 --> 00:14:04,485
and say they're cooperating.

260
00:14:04,882 --> 00:14:05,462
but they're not.

261
00:14:05,822 --> 00:14:07,184
They're not at all cooperating,

262
00:14:07,204 --> 00:14:09,906
but the player writes that story for themselves.

263
00:14:10,387 --> 00:14:12,709
And that is our little emergent story

264
00:14:12,769 --> 00:14:14,811
every time slimes are hungry and they wanna get out.

265
00:14:15,851 --> 00:14:16,852
There's also flying,

266
00:14:17,493 --> 00:14:20,235
which is perceived as rescuing a lot of the time.

267
00:14:21,076 --> 00:14:23,098
Foster slimes can fly, simple as that.

268
00:14:23,398 --> 00:14:24,960
But if they're stacked at the time,

269
00:14:25,380 --> 00:14:28,163
they will carry whatever is underneath them away.

270
00:14:28,203 --> 00:14:29,744
And there's really no limit to that.

271
00:14:30,865 --> 00:14:33,186
And this was once again a happy accident.

272
00:14:33,646 --> 00:14:36,668
We knew they could fly and then later we added the stacking

273
00:14:37,029 --> 00:14:38,209
and then we just saw one of them

274
00:14:38,309 --> 00:14:39,770
carrying his buddy away one day.

275
00:14:39,790 --> 00:14:41,091
We're like this is amazing.

276
00:14:41,892 --> 00:14:44,793
But it used to be that they could just fly infinitely

277
00:14:44,813 --> 00:14:46,474
and every once in a while they still get away with that

278
00:14:46,715 --> 00:14:48,416
and we're kind of okay with it

279
00:14:48,576 --> 00:14:51,217
because it just sort of reads as like

280
00:14:51,377 --> 00:14:52,858
they really wanted to get away.

281
00:14:52,918 --> 00:14:55,760
Like those two are buddies, they're a bonded pair.

282
00:14:56,180 --> 00:14:58,441
they're going to start a life together and that's okay.

283
00:14:59,622 --> 00:15:04,144
So we love this and half of it, like I said, was accidents

284
00:15:04,684 --> 00:15:08,006
and that is sort of half of the player experience as well.

285
00:15:08,346 --> 00:15:09,907
It's going to seem like accidents,

286
00:15:09,987 --> 00:15:11,648
these collisions of things.

287
00:15:13,028 --> 00:15:15,309
And we have some that seem kind of,

288
00:15:16,330 --> 00:15:17,950
they're more subtle, like stealing.

289
00:15:17,970 --> 00:15:21,272
A tabby slime, if anybody owns a cat,

290
00:15:21,292 --> 00:15:23,233
they'll know every once in a while you find this

291
00:15:23,273 --> 00:15:25,734
treasure trove of bottle caps and other garbage

292
00:15:25,794 --> 00:15:27,635
that they really love.

293
00:15:28,655 --> 00:15:30,076
Tabby slimes do a similar thing.

294
00:15:30,096 --> 00:15:35,278
If they find food that they can't eat,

295
00:15:35,658 --> 00:15:37,779
one of their wants that we coded for them is

296
00:15:38,200 --> 00:15:39,340
find food I can't eat.

297
00:15:40,181 --> 00:15:42,447
take it to another location where food is.

298
00:15:43,911 --> 00:15:46,919
That is really what makes tabby slimes kind of difficult.

299
00:15:48,044 --> 00:15:51,785
And this plays out in so many different ways

300
00:15:51,925 --> 00:15:53,345
and that's the best part of it.

301
00:15:53,765 --> 00:15:57,147
We didn't make the behavior super obvious.

302
00:15:57,907 --> 00:16:00,428
We didn't add any other layers to it.

303
00:16:00,688 --> 00:16:03,989
By keeping it simple, it's like open connection points.

304
00:16:04,489 --> 00:16:07,450
It allows it to receive the connections

305
00:16:07,550 --> 00:16:09,891
from all these other wants and needs out there.

306
00:16:09,931 --> 00:16:11,791
The more specific you make something,

307
00:16:12,072 --> 00:16:13,632
the more limited it's going to be.

308
00:16:14,312 --> 00:16:17,313
So if like tabby slimes only stole carrots.

309
00:16:18,515 --> 00:16:19,096
at night

310
00:16:19,797 --> 00:16:25,828
And blah blah blah like you're the players just going to miss it so you make it as open as possible

311
00:16:26,328 --> 00:16:27,250
in the case of stealing

312
00:16:29,361 --> 00:16:34,286
he's taking food from one food pile basically to another that he's creating.

313
00:16:35,567 --> 00:16:39,851
If the player observes that alone, they say, oh look, it's just like a normal cat.

314
00:16:40,471 --> 00:16:46,617
It's hoarding treasure. If other slimes are eating at the food pile at point B,

315
00:16:47,138 --> 00:16:51,682
the player says, oh look, the tabby slimes, they bring food to other slimes. They're so charitable.

316
00:16:52,702 --> 00:16:54,363
If other slimes are eating over here,

317
00:16:54,403 --> 00:16:57,104
they say tabby slimes steal food from other slimes.

318
00:16:57,124 --> 00:16:58,964
They're so sly like that.

319
00:16:59,404 --> 00:17:00,785
And that's the beauty of the system.

320
00:17:01,125 --> 00:17:02,765
They're not interacting with one another.

321
00:17:03,605 --> 00:17:06,726
Slimes just have a want, or a need to eat,

322
00:17:06,806 --> 00:17:07,907
so they're gonna be there anyway.

323
00:17:08,687 --> 00:17:10,547
And sometimes they bring that carrot over,

324
00:17:11,068 --> 00:17:12,328
and that carrot shouldn't be there

325
00:17:12,348 --> 00:17:14,008
because the other food pile was all fruit,

326
00:17:14,589 --> 00:17:16,909
and the largos that ate over there

327
00:17:16,929 --> 00:17:18,190
then caused a tar outbreak

328
00:17:18,250 --> 00:17:20,910
because we've just introduced foreign matter over there.

329
00:17:21,771 --> 00:17:24,673
and so it's, you know, this chain reaction.

330
00:17:26,594 --> 00:17:32,579
Next is explosions, which these probably come the closest

331
00:17:32,599 --> 00:17:35,501
to this like highly specific behavior

332
00:17:35,541 --> 00:17:37,542
that doesn't have as many connection points,

333
00:17:38,082 --> 00:17:39,904
but it's really a player hazard.

334
00:17:40,384 --> 00:17:42,005
These slimes are, boom slimes,

335
00:17:42,145 --> 00:17:43,686
are designed to be more difficult.

336
00:17:43,807 --> 00:17:44,947
Their plorts are more valuable.

337
00:17:45,852 --> 00:17:47,113
So it's really kind of a balanced thing.

338
00:17:47,214 --> 00:17:53,179
However, its entire purpose is to just impulse things away.

339
00:17:53,580 --> 00:17:55,181
So it's like the tabby behavior,

340
00:17:55,221 --> 00:17:58,024
but it's whatever happens to be around it in all directions.

341
00:17:58,624 --> 00:18:01,407
And that includes actors, that includes resources,

342
00:18:01,447 --> 00:18:03,269
it includes all the pieces.

343
00:18:03,749 --> 00:18:05,730
that drive our emergent behaviors.

344
00:18:05,830 --> 00:18:07,671
Everything in Slime Rancher is just driven by

345
00:18:08,011 --> 00:18:10,292
slimes wanting to, or slimes intersecting

346
00:18:10,332 --> 00:18:11,793
with resources primarily.

347
00:18:12,273 --> 00:18:15,775
And so by adding a slime that booms everything away from it,

348
00:18:18,957 --> 00:18:22,778
just view that as chaos, but it has a very, very specific purpose.

349
00:18:23,178 --> 00:18:27,580
And especially in the wild, it causes things to go where they shouldn't.

350
00:18:28,020 --> 00:18:31,101
So in every, out in the wild, in Slime Rancher,

351
00:18:31,141 --> 00:18:34,562
we like to think of each sort of room that makes up the world as a cell.

352
00:18:35,162 --> 00:18:38,903
And within a cell, our designers will very specifically put

353
00:18:39,824 --> 00:18:42,105
hubs of activity in certain spaces.

354
00:18:42,665 --> 00:18:43,945
And the idea is that...

355
00:18:44,525 --> 00:18:46,486
in the beginning, slimes who want to eat this food

356
00:18:46,526 --> 00:18:48,846
and that food and this food kind of stay in that area,

357
00:18:49,147 --> 00:18:50,847
but if you sit in the areas long enough

358
00:18:50,967 --> 00:18:52,407
or you happen to be close to them

359
00:18:52,768 --> 00:18:55,748
and they're live long enough that they're working

360
00:18:56,108 --> 00:18:58,649
while you're not viewing it, cross-pollination occurs.

361
00:18:59,149 --> 00:19:01,050
And so when cross-pollination occurs,

362
00:19:01,090 --> 00:19:03,190
you get the largos and then eventually you get the tar.

363
00:19:03,750 --> 00:19:06,593
So anytime you enter a cell in Slime Rancher

364
00:19:06,613 --> 00:19:08,415
and the tar are already overtaking it,

365
00:19:08,795 --> 00:19:10,797
it's because that was sort of cooking in the background

366
00:19:10,877 --> 00:19:12,178
long enough for that to happen.

367
00:19:12,218 --> 00:19:14,220
It is never going to just happen.

368
00:19:14,981 --> 00:19:16,242
We don't do it that way.

369
00:19:16,702 --> 00:19:19,785
So stuff like boom slimes that are impulsing things

370
00:19:20,245 --> 00:19:22,988
in all directions are causing that cross-pollination

371
00:19:23,008 --> 00:19:24,489
to happen much, much faster.

372
00:19:25,645 --> 00:19:28,646
And then the final cherry on top for the design

373
00:19:28,766 --> 00:19:29,986
is the backpack itself.

374
00:19:31,087 --> 00:19:33,267
The primary player action in Slime Rancher

375
00:19:33,327 --> 00:19:35,568
causes slimes, food, et cetera, to come together

376
00:19:35,608 --> 00:19:38,149
and interact further, encouraging emergent behaviors.

377
00:19:39,190 --> 00:19:41,971
So if all other systems that I just described

378
00:19:42,311 --> 00:19:44,632
completely fall on their ass, we have.

379
00:19:44,992 --> 00:19:46,855
the VACPAC as the great equalizer,

380
00:19:47,235 --> 00:19:48,858
because at the very least,

381
00:19:49,278 --> 00:19:50,760
everything that the player does

382
00:19:50,860 --> 00:19:52,763
in order to drive the action in the game

383
00:19:52,783 --> 00:19:54,065
to accomplish their objectives

384
00:19:54,486 --> 00:19:57,130
is bringing slimes and resources together.

385
00:19:57,150 --> 00:19:59,233
And so in doing so...

386
00:19:59,913 --> 00:20:02,674
they're literally just firing off emergent behaviors

387
00:20:02,754 --> 00:20:04,835
if they were to interrupt that process at any point,

388
00:20:04,875 --> 00:20:06,815
which they do when they see something they want,

389
00:20:06,855 --> 00:20:09,136
when they see a gold slime, when a tar attacks them,

390
00:20:09,376 --> 00:20:10,556
when they fall off a cliff,

391
00:20:10,596 --> 00:20:12,257
when a tabby slime boops their nose.

392
00:20:12,697 --> 00:20:13,917
Any of those things are designed

393
00:20:13,937 --> 00:20:16,058
to sort of interrupt that action.

394
00:20:16,798 --> 00:20:18,178
We always sort of saw Slime Rancher

395
00:20:18,238 --> 00:20:21,359
as like sort of chaos management,

396
00:20:21,479 --> 00:20:25,020
and this is the reason why the vac tanks are so limited.

397
00:20:26,001 --> 00:20:28,102
is that I want the player to say,

398
00:20:28,242 --> 00:20:29,943
oh I want some of this, oh I'm all full,

399
00:20:30,023 --> 00:20:32,245
oh those guys are about to mix with this,

400
00:20:32,285 --> 00:20:33,025
I don't want that to happen,

401
00:20:33,045 --> 00:20:35,307
so I'll vac them up and just fire them over my shoulder

402
00:20:35,327 --> 00:20:36,948
to get rid of them so I can then get at

403
00:20:37,028 --> 00:20:38,009
whatever's happening here.

404
00:20:38,029 --> 00:20:41,311
Well in doing so, you're causing more chain reactions

405
00:20:41,351 --> 00:20:42,331
to occur behind you.

406
00:20:42,732 --> 00:20:44,793
So the vac pack really does a great job

407
00:20:44,813 --> 00:20:45,674
of accomplishing this.

408
00:20:48,916 --> 00:20:51,898
So finally, I have a couple of thoughts

409
00:20:52,258 --> 00:20:53,459
on emergent storytelling.

410
00:20:54,704 --> 00:20:55,765
before I wrap up here.

411
00:20:57,567 --> 00:21:00,849
The first one is that only half the story matters.

412
00:21:02,010 --> 00:21:05,373
So not only can these stories be really, really short,

413
00:21:05,854 --> 00:21:07,755
but only half of it actually matters.

414
00:21:08,536 --> 00:21:11,058
Players don't need to observe this chain reaction

415
00:21:11,098 --> 00:21:13,640
or this sequence in its entirety to appreciate it.

416
00:21:14,701 --> 00:21:16,361
In the example of the tabby slime,

417
00:21:17,501 --> 00:21:21,382
just seeing a tabby slime arrive with a carrot in its mouth

418
00:21:21,462 --> 00:21:22,983
to other slimes and drop it there,

419
00:21:23,423 --> 00:21:25,423
they just say, well, a tabby slime came out of nowhere

420
00:21:25,463 --> 00:21:26,504
and started feeding this guy.

421
00:21:27,424 --> 00:21:29,825
Had they observed the first part of that,

422
00:21:29,865 --> 00:21:32,285
they would say, oh wait, no, a tabby slime stole a carrot

423
00:21:32,385 --> 00:21:34,006
from another slime and is giving it to another,

424
00:21:34,026 --> 00:21:36,006
so maybe it likes these slimes, I'm not sure.

425
00:21:36,026 --> 00:21:37,747
And if they only saw the beginning,

426
00:21:38,047 --> 00:21:40,748
they might view it as the tabby slime stole the carrot

427
00:21:41,288 --> 00:21:45,730
and probably is going to keep it for himself and went off into some place that I didn't see.

428
00:21:46,130 --> 00:21:50,231
So there's A, B, C there and it doesn't matter which parts you see, it's a story to you.

429
00:21:51,432 --> 00:21:56,974
They'll figure it out later too when they finally observe that tabby slime take care of it from point A to point B,

430
00:21:57,034 --> 00:22:01,676
they can then start using that information so now when they are corralling tabby slimes,

431
00:22:01,976 --> 00:22:05,097
they have that and they feel rewarded for learning this behavior.

432
00:22:05,237 --> 00:22:10,600
It will still take them by surprise though because the neat thing about wants is they're kind of unreliable.

433
00:22:11,540 --> 00:22:15,503
A tabby slime is not going to always steal a carrot,

434
00:22:15,783 --> 00:22:18,004
but a tabby slime when it's hungry will always want to eat.

435
00:22:18,505 --> 00:22:20,646
And that kind of takes me back to

436
00:22:20,666 --> 00:22:23,628
our needs need to be limited

437
00:22:24,029 --> 00:22:25,970
and they need to be manageable.

438
00:22:26,350 --> 00:22:28,792
Because if they all of a sudden said,

439
00:22:28,832 --> 00:22:30,453
well every time I work with tabby slimes

440
00:22:30,473 --> 00:22:32,114
now I gotta work on this stealing thing

441
00:22:32,134 --> 00:22:33,455
and that it just becomes too much

442
00:22:33,555 --> 00:22:35,516
and you're just managing lists at that point.

443
00:22:37,557 --> 00:22:40,179
Finally, players are in on the joke

444
00:22:40,419 --> 00:22:42,321
when it comes to emergent storytelling.

445
00:22:43,321 --> 00:22:45,423
Emergent behaviors can disrupt the experience,

446
00:22:45,463 --> 00:22:46,944
like truly disrupt the experience.

447
00:22:46,984 --> 00:22:48,986
It can cause the player to die unexpectedly

448
00:22:49,046 --> 00:22:50,087
when they were in the middle of trying

449
00:22:50,107 --> 00:22:51,828
to accomplish an objective, and that sucks.

450
00:22:52,409 --> 00:22:55,251
But it rarely breaks immersion.

451
00:22:56,192 --> 00:22:57,813
In fact, it is often the most memorable

452
00:22:57,853 --> 00:22:58,914
part of the experience.

453
00:23:00,115 --> 00:23:02,017
So an example of that would be if,

454
00:23:03,638 --> 00:23:09,884
you were playing a first-person shooter and an enemy soldier that you had in your sights was just walking, running in place,

455
00:23:10,384 --> 00:23:14,068
screaming that he was going to kill you, but into a wall, walking in place.

456
00:23:14,989 --> 00:23:19,953
That in a way is a sort of emergent behavior because it wasn't intended, but it is flat-out a bug.

457
00:23:20,254 --> 00:23:23,117
It is not contributing to this sort of surprising

458
00:23:23,857 --> 00:23:24,178
event.

459
00:23:25,118 --> 00:23:27,619
So when a player encounters a bug like that,

460
00:23:27,819 --> 00:23:29,359
it pulls them immediately out of the experience.

461
00:23:29,399 --> 00:23:31,560
They immediately say, oh, this game was coded so poorly.

462
00:23:31,580 --> 00:23:34,481
This sucks, the AI in this game is bad.

463
00:23:35,541 --> 00:23:39,162
But if instead, let's take a similar sort of broken action

464
00:23:39,602 --> 00:23:41,343
where an enemy soldier's screaming at you,

465
00:23:41,363 --> 00:23:44,264
he's about to kill you, and he goes to throw that grenade,

466
00:23:44,664 --> 00:23:47,244
and another enemy soldier who was trying to come at you

467
00:23:47,284 --> 00:23:49,225
gets in front of it and it bops off of his head

468
00:23:49,325 --> 00:23:50,746
and it lands at the feet of the guy

469
00:23:50,786 --> 00:23:52,866
who immediately threw it, who's still looking seriously

470
00:23:52,926 --> 00:23:54,207
at you and then just explodes.

471
00:23:54,967 --> 00:23:56,727
that's totally kind of a bug,

472
00:23:57,588 --> 00:23:59,788
or at least not at all intended,

473
00:23:59,948 --> 00:24:01,449
and the player will love that.

474
00:24:01,589 --> 00:24:02,969
They will say, they'll either think

475
00:24:03,149 --> 00:24:04,510
they were responsible for it,

476
00:24:04,750 --> 00:24:05,870
they'll think it's hilarious,

477
00:24:06,230 --> 00:24:08,751
but the important thing is it had a beginning

478
00:24:08,791 --> 00:24:09,711
and a middle and an end.

479
00:24:10,892 --> 00:24:12,812
When the soldier is just running into the wall,

480
00:24:13,072 --> 00:24:15,913
it doesn't have an end, and it just sits there,

481
00:24:15,953 --> 00:24:16,914
it doesn't do anything.

482
00:24:17,914 --> 00:24:19,895
So in Skyrim, for example,

483
00:24:19,915 --> 00:24:22,716
it's like the, you know, if you can...

484
00:24:24,617 --> 00:24:28,020
use these things that seem like bugs as emergent behaviors.

485
00:24:28,040 --> 00:24:29,962
For example, collecting a bunch of townspeople

486
00:24:30,022 --> 00:24:31,324
somehow to fight a dragon.

487
00:24:32,465 --> 00:24:34,427
That was never probably intended,

488
00:24:34,447 --> 00:24:37,310
and it looks ridiculous when the barmaid is swinging a rag

489
00:24:37,370 --> 00:24:38,631
trying to kill a dragon.

490
00:24:39,392 --> 00:24:40,752
But again, players love that.

491
00:24:40,852 --> 00:24:43,093
That is like a notch in their belt.

492
00:24:43,233 --> 00:24:44,854
That is part of their heroic journey

493
00:24:44,894 --> 00:24:47,975
and it's equal to when they were like climbing up a mountain

494
00:24:48,015 --> 00:24:49,416
and taking on a dragon solo.

495
00:24:49,456 --> 00:24:51,117
They will remember that the most.

496
00:24:51,797 --> 00:24:54,378
So my final takeaway is that your game

497
00:24:54,398 --> 00:24:56,259
will be more memorable, more interesting,

498
00:24:56,319 --> 00:24:59,020
and have more variety if you add even a little capacity

499
00:24:59,040 --> 00:25:00,101
for emergent storytelling.

500
00:25:00,221 --> 00:25:03,442
It is one of the few ways games can still truly surprise.

501
00:25:04,743 --> 00:25:05,703
So thank you very much.

502
00:25:13,664 --> 00:25:15,445
I think now we're going to take some questions.

503
00:25:15,645 --> 00:25:17,566
Yeah, just make sure you come up to the mics in the aisles

504
00:25:17,646 --> 00:25:18,166
if you have a question.

